// 1. Binary Search Tree (BST)
//     Time Complexity: 
//         Best case: O(log n) (balanced BST)
//         Worst case: O(n) (unbalanced BST)
//     Observed Results:
//       Insert and search times are relatively higher compared to BTree due to potential unbalancing, where operations may degrade to O(n).
//       Update is faster because it doesn’t involve rebalancing.
//       Removal is not tested (observed as 0 ms), which could indicate an oversight or lack of implementation for the test case.

// 2. AVL Tree
//     Time Complexity:
//          O(log n)
//     Observed Results:
//       Slightly slower than BST in Insert and Remove operations because AVL requires rotations to maintain balance, adding overhead.
//       Search is nearly equivalent to BST since both are logarithmic in balanced cases.
//       Update (similar to insert and remove) includes balancing overhead, making it slower than BST but faster than BTree for such operations.

// 3. BTree
//     Time Complexity:
//           O(log n)
//     Observed Results:
//       Extremely fast for Insert, Search, Update, and Remove compared to BST and AVL. The observed times confirm the theoretical optimization of BTrees for batched diskaccessfriendly operations.
//       The very low times indicate superior performance due to reduced overhead from fewer levels and efficient node splitting.
